      "Aquarius needs exercise that engages their mind as well as their body — or that is social enough to provide the sense of community they value. Team sports, group fitness classes with an innovative twist, martial arts, and any activity with an intellectual or strategic component appeal to them. They are drawn to unconventional exercise — aerial yoga, parkour, underwater hockey, and whatever the newest, most unusual fitness trend is. Technology-enhanced fitness like VR workouts, fitness tracking with data analysis, and gamified exercise programs suit their tech-oriented nature. They exercise best when the activity feels like an experience rather than an obligation, and they are more consistent when exercise has a social or community component. Solo, repetitive exercise like treadmill running bores them quickly unless they're listening to a podcast interesting enough to make them forget they're exercising.",

    mentalHealth:
      "Aquarius's mental health is closely tied to their sense of belonging and purpose. While they value independence, prolonged isolation can trigger depression that manifests as detachment from reality, a flattening of emotional affect, and a retreat into intellectual abstraction that loses touch with the embodied, relational aspects of life. Anxiety for Aquarius often presents as racing thoughts, insomnia, and a feeling of being wired but unable to focus — reflecting the overstimulated nervous system that Uranus governs. They may struggle with attention regulation, finding it difficult to sustain focus on one thing while their mind constantly generates new connections and ideas. Social anxiety can paradoxically coexist with their social nature — they may be comfortable in groups organized around ideas but intensely uncomfortable in emotionally intimate settings. The best mental health support for Aquarius combines intellectual respect with gentle emotional challenge — therapy that validates their analytical nature while persistently inviting them to inhabit their emotional and physical experience rather than hovering above it.",

